content: i think the most important question is who are we designing our community centers, who are the users and demographics
When considering the design of a community center, identifying the users and demographics is indeed a crucial step
However, this question opens up a multitude of perspectives and trade-offs that can significantly influence your design approach
Think about the diverse needs that different user groups might have
For instance, seniors might prioritize accessibility and quiet spaces, while teenagers might be more interested in areas for socializing and activities
Families with young children could value safe play areas, whereas local artists might seek spaces for exhibitions or workshops
If you focus too narrowly, you might exclude potential users, but if you try to cater to everyone, you might dilute the effectiveness of the space for any one group
In the context of your community center project, reflect on the local community's unique characteristics
What cultural, social, or economic factors are at play
